===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|en|ang|for-}}, which is identical with the preposition "{{m|en|for}}". In "Old English and Middle English it occurs frequently as a variant of {{m|en|fore-}} prefix, with the senses ‚Äòbefore‚Äô, ‚Äòin front‚Äô, ‚Äòon behalf of‚Äô, etc.; cf. Old English for-, forecuman to come before, Middle English forganger and foreganger n."<ref name="oed-for2">Oxford English Dictionary, s.v. ‚Äúfor- (prefix2),‚Äù March 2024, https://doi.org/10.1093/OED/1183476270.</ref>

====Prefix====
{{en-prefix}}

# {{senseid|en|before}} {{alt form|en|fore-|id=before}}.
#: {{uxi|en|[[forstand|'''for'''stand]]}} is to stand in front of so as to bar the way, {{uxi|en|[[fordede|'''for'''dede]]}} is a deed done for another, {{uxi|en|[[forlead|'''for'''lead]]}} is alternative form of forelead (‚Äúlead forward, lead before‚Äù)

===Etymology 3===
"Occurring only in words adopted from French, as forcatch v., forfeit n., forprise n., represents Old French for-, fors-, identical with fors adv. (modern French hors) outside, out."<ref name="oed-for3">Oxford English Dictionary, s.v. ‚Äúfor- (prefix3),‚Äù September 2023, https://doi.org/10.1093/OED/8923913950.</ref>

