==Danish==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|da|non|for-}}, from {{inh|da|gem-pro|*fra-}}.

===Prefix===
{{da-prefix}}

# {{ng|Makes verbs from adjectives meaning "to cause to be [adjective]".}}
#: {{prefixusex|da|sk√∏n|t1=beautiful|-e|pos2=infinitive suffix|forsk√∏nne|t3=beautify}}
#: {{prefixusex|da|s√∏d|t1=sweet|-e|fors√∏de|t3=sweeten}}
#: {{prefixusex|da|uren|t1=unclean|-e|forurene|t3=pollute}}
# {{ng|Denotes initial or preparatory action; {{m|en|pre-}}.}}
#: {{prefixusex|da|bore|t1=drill|forbore|t2=drill a hole for screwing}}
#: {{prefixusex|da|arbejde|t1=work|forarbejde|t2=preparatory work}}

====Usage notes====
This element appears in a great number of adapted loanwords from German, Low German and Dutch, to render ''ver-'' or ''vor-'', such as in {{m|da|ford√¶rve||to decay, to rot}}. In these cases, it may represent senses that are no longer, or never were, productive in Danish.

